\begin_layout Paragraph*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset(X,T)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=A$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
First prove if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=A.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 then any neighboorhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, which is also in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin A$
\end_inset

 then the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash A$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap(X\backslash A)=\{\}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Now prove if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=A$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 is a closure we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 contains its contact points.
 Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

is not a contact point.
 Therefore we know that for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood with an open interior 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cap\bar{A}=\{\}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we can take of open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that do not intersect with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 .
 We know this union will equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 because we have included an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 and that none of the open neighborhoods intersect with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the infinite union of open set is is open, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 is open and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=A$
\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

