\begin_inset Formula $(X,T)$
\end_inset

, prove that a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open iff every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 has an open neighborhood contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
First prove if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 has an open neighborhood contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
If every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 has an open neighborhood contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 then we can union all of these neighborhoods togethor to get 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is included, and each set is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A,$
\end_inset

we know we get 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since each neighborhod was open we know their union 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must also be open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Now prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is open then every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 has an open neighborhood contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
